{"relationshipsSections":[{"type":"conformsTo","kind":"relationships","title":"Conforms To","identifiers":["doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/Animatable","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/s15BitwiseCopyableP","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/s8CopyableP","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/SQ","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/SH","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/s8SendableP"]}],"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"declarations","declarations":[{"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"],"tokens":[{"kind":"attribute","text":"@frozen"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"keyword","text":"struct"},{"kind":"text","text":" "},{"kind":"identifier","text":"UnitPoint"}]}]},{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"overview","type":"heading","text":"Overview","level":2},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Use a unit point to represent a location in a view without having to know","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"the view’s rendered size. The point stores a value in each dimension that","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"indicates the fraction of the view’s size in that dimension — measured","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"from the view’s origin — where the point appears. For example, you can","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"create a unit point that represents the center of any view by using the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"value ","type":"text"},{"code":"0.5","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" for each dimension:","type":"text"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["let unitPoint = UnitPoint(x: 0.5, y: 0.5)"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To project the unit point into the rendered view’s coordinate space,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"multiply each component of the unit point with the corresponding"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"component of the view’s size:"}]},{"syntax":"swift","type":"codeListing","code":["let projectedPoint = CGPoint(","    x: unitPoint.x * size.width,","    y: unitPoint.y * size.height",")"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You can perform this calculation yourself if you happen to know a view’s","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"size, or if you want to use the unit point for some custom purpose, but","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"OpenSwiftUI typically does this for you to carry out operations that","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"you request, like when you:","type":"text"}]},{"items":[{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Transform a shape using a shape modifier. For example, to rotate a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"shape with ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"Shape\/rotation(_:anchor:)"},{"text":", you indicate an anchor point","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"that you want to rotate the shape around.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Override the alignment of the view in a ","type":"text"},{"code":"Grid","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" cell using the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"View\/gridCellAnchor(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" view modifier. The grid aligns the projection","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"of a unit point onto the view with the projection of the same unit point","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"onto the cell.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Create a gradient that has a center, or start and stop points, relative","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"to the shape that you are styling. See the gradient methods in","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/ShapeStyle","isActive":true,"type":"reference"},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}],"type":"unorderedList"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You can create custom unit points with explicit values, like the example","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"above, or you can use one of the built-in unit points that OpenSwiftUI provides,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"like ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/zero"},{"text":", ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/center"},{"text":", or ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/topTrailing"},{"text":". The built-in values","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"correspond to the alignment positions of the similarly named, built-in","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"isActive":true,"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/Alignment"},{"text":" types.","type":"text"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"A unit point with one or more components outside the range "},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"[0, 1]"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"projects to a point outside of the view."}],"type":"paragraph"}],"type":"aside","style":"note","name":"Note"},{"anchor":"Layout-direction","type":"heading","text":"Layout direction","level":3},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"When a person configures their device to use a left-to-right language like"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"English, the system places the view’s origin in its top-left corner,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"with positive x toward the right and positive y toward the bottom of the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"view. In a right-to-left environment, the origin moves to the upper-right"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"corner, and the positive x direction changes to be toward the left. You"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"don’t typically need to do anything to handle this change, because OpenSwiftUI"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"applies the change to all aspects of the system. For example, see the"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"discussion about layout direction in "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/HorizontalAlignment","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":"."}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"It’s important to test your app for the different locales that you"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"distribute your app in. For more information about the localization process,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"see "},{"identifier":"https:\/\/developer.apple.com\/documentation\/xcode\/localization","type":"reference","isActive":true}]}]}],"topicSections":[{"anchor":"Initializers","generated":true,"title":"Initializers","identifiers":["doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/init()","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/init(x:y:)"]},{"anchor":"Instance-Properties","generated":true,"title":"Instance Properties","identifiers":["doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/x","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/y"]},{"anchor":"Type-Properties","generated":true,"title":"Type Properties","identifiers":["doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/bottom","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/bottomLeading","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/bottomTrailing","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/center","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/leading","doc:\/\/OpenSwiftUI\/documentation\/OpenSwiftUI\/UnitPoint\/top","doc:\/\/Ope